d States (Susan Christopherson) and in an urban context in Montreal (Damaris Rose and Paul Villeneuve), the effect of gentrification on women's work roles (Liz Bondi), inequality in the work force (Sylvia Gold), and theoretical issues involved in understanding women in the contemporary city (Linda Peake). An introductory essay provides a review of current issues. Feminists and women's studies specialists and activists as well as geographers, historians, sociologists, and policy planners will find this book of great interest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh1 aBenenson, Hal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBondi, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradbury, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristopherson, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGold, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaye, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKobayashi, Audrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParr, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeake, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPickles, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Damaris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVilleneuve, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077